<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-174-376  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 174 376.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Feb 19 1990 n578 p33(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Waveguides ride photonic ICs.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bindra, Ashok.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>AT and T Bell Laboratories report they have successfullyfabricated two photonic integrated circuits (IC) that pave the wayfor exploitation of nearly the entire frequency range of theoptical spectrum for fiber-optic communications.andP;  The ICsincorporate low-loss optical waveguides to integrate lasers,amplifiers, switchers, filters and detectors on a single die.andP;  Thetwo chips, one a balanced heterodyne receiver and the other alight transmission source, both are made of indium galliumarsenide phosphide on an indium phosphide substrate, grown usingvapor-phase techniques.andP;  With the help of these ICs, opticalfibers will be able to carry thousands of voice channels ordigital high-definition television signals.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   AT and T Bell Laboratories Inc. (research).andO;Topic:     Fiber OpticsIntegrated CircuitsData CommunicationsSemiconductor PreparationReceiversTransmitters.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Bell Labs' multiplexing light source. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>